Findings:
Abdomen
Right lateral views were initially provided. Opposite lateral and VD views were acquired after radiologist's request. There is quantum mottling to varying degrees in all images most notably in the cranial abdomen. 

There is normal serosal margin detail in the mid to caudal abdomen; assessment of the cranial abdomen is hindered by quantum mottling (i.e. underexposure) artifact. In the initial right lateral views, there is the impression of small intestinal plication in the cranial to mid ventral abdomen. In the subsequent images, the small intestinal segments in this region of the abdomen no long contain gas but there is a continue impression of at least small intestinal bunching in the cranial to mid ventral abdomen in the additionally provided images. The remaining visible intra-abdominal structures are normal.
Conclusions:
The appearance of the small intestine in the cranial to mid ventral abdomen is concerning but not conclusive for a linear foreign body obstruction and secondary intestinal plication. Quantum mottling artifact in the cranial abdomen hinders assessment to some degree. 

Medical management overnight and repeat abdominal imaging (ideally abdominal ultrasound as repeat abdominal radiographs may have the same technical issues which could further assessment) could be considered. Alternatively, given history, exploratory laparotomy could be considered.

Findings:
Previous 2 radiographs (Thoracic VD and lateral Abdomen) compared with the single lateral thoracic image. The most ventral aspect of the abdomen is outside of the area of collimation. 

*   There is an increased volume of gas within the pleural space, compared to the previous images, causing marked retraction of the pleural lung margins (R>>L) and increased distance between the cardiac silhouette and diaphragm. The right cranial and middle lung lobes are completely opacified and reduced in volume in the previous images. There is a persistent mild to moderate unstructured interstitial pattern throughout the rest of the lung lobes. 
*   The cardiac silhouette and pulmonary vasculature remain normal.  
*   The mediastinal structures remain normal. 
*   The stomach is mildly distended with gas and a small volume of heterogeneous soft tissue opacity with multiple small mineral foci in the previous images, most likely representing postprandial/atypical gastric ingesta.
*   Osteophytosis of the stifle joint with medial luxation of one of the patellae.
*   The rest of the abdominal structures are normal.
Conclusions:
*   Progressive moderate to severe pneumothorax, with atelectasis of the lung lobes (presumed worse on the right cranial and middle, based on the previous study) - such as idiopathic/spontaneous or traumatic. Concurrent pulmonary pathology in the right cranial and middle lung lobes cannot be entirely ruled out (e.g., contusions, pneumonia > neoplasia).
*   Stifle osteoarthrosis with medial patellar luxation.
*   A cause for the neurological abnormalities is not identified.

Findings:
Two radiographs are availalbe for interpretation dated June 17, 2025. They are right lateral and ventrodorsal radiographs of the combined thorax and abdomen. 

On the VD view, there is left lateralized fluid/soft tissue opacity occupying the left pleural space with what appears to be retracted left caudal lung. There is concurrent suspect mild leftward mediastinal shift. On the right lateral view this left pleural opacity is not as well appreciated and there is a hazy increased opacity summating with the perihilar to caudodorsal region and cranioventral thorax, and a pleural fissure or lobar sign overlying the caudal margin of the silhouette, suggesting pleural effusion. The right sided pumonary parenchyma appears normal on the VD view despite a fairly generalized haziness to the parenchyma on the lateral view. There is the appearance of vascular congestion near the hilus on the lateral views, however, vessels seem normal on the VD view. Cardiac silhouette is considered normal in size and shape. No evidence of rib lesion or other significant thoracic musculoskeletal abnormality. 

The peritoneal detail is normal within the abdomen. On the lateral view only there is a patchy increased softt issue opacity dorsal to the kidneys and ventral to L1-L3. Also, a few round to ovoid soft tissue nodular opacities are summating with the caudal retroperitoneal space.The liver is mildly diffusely enlarged with normal margination. The gastrointestinal tract is normal. The urinary bladder is small and normal in opacity. There is a well-defined ovoid mineral opaque nodule with discrete peripheral rim int he carnioventral abdomen.
Conclusions:
\- The radiographs are concerning for left sided unilateral pleural effusion which given the history and lateralization is most concerning for pyothorax. There is suspect atelectasis subsequently of the left lungs though a pulmonary infectious infiltrate is also possible. An underlying pleural and/or pulmonary neoplasia (carcinoma) with pleural effusion or hemorrahge is not ruled out. Thoracocentesis (ultrasound guided if possible) is recommended, followed by cytology and culture of any fluid acquired. Pyothorax is managed ideally with culture of fluid, chest tube placement and flushing, though sometimes non-responsive cases require advanced imaging (CT of thorax) with thoracotomy. Medical management solely is not ideal but also not wrong to attempt when other avenues are unavailable. Heart failure is considered less likely given the unilaterality of the changes and lack of cardiomegaly, however, the mild vascular congestion does suggest some degree of increased circulatory fluid or cardiac overload; would recommend discontinuing steroids in case a pre-existing cardiac condition is present that prediposes patient to fluid/circulatory overload and failure. Given the time lapse repeat three view (left, right and either DV or VD) thoracic radiographs collimated to the thorax (from thoracic inlet to mid stomach) could be considered to re-evaluate and see if any changes have allowed for better visualization of pleural versus pulmonary versus cardiovascular pathology. 
\-  The patchy increased opacity dorsal to renal silhouette on lateral view may be summation artifact with vascualture and splenic head/body, however mild perinephric steatitis and/or effusion, such as from pyelonephritis or other renal disease, is not entirely ruled out. Correlate to laboratory findings and/or urinalysis. 
\- Mild hepatomegaly is non-specific and may be a benign incidental finding, however, inflammation or less likely neoplasia are not ruled out. 
\- Small nodular soft tissue opacities superimposed with the caudal retroperitoneal space on lateral view may be incidentally conspicuous lymph nodes, end-on vasculature artifact, or mildly enlarged lymph nodes.
\- Mineralized nodule of the cranioventral abdomen is most consistent with an incidental Bates body/fat necrosis.
Conditions_List: pleural effusion: false (negated) | pleural effusion: indeterminate (uncertain) | pleural effusion: indeterminate (uncertain) | Heart failure: true (affirmed) | cardiomegaly: false (negated)

Findings:
Three-view thoracic radiographs. Five total JPEG images. Ungloved human anatomy is present at the periphery of the right lateral projection, which is a significant breach in radiation safety.

The cardiac silhouette is on the upper limits of normal (VHS = 10.5). There is mild flattening of the caudal cardiac waist. The pulmonary vasculature is normal. The pulmonary parenchyma has a mild bronchial and patchy unstructured interstitial pattern. No regions of consolidation or soft tissue opaque nodules are identified within the pulmonary parenchyma. There is dynamic widening and narrowing of the mainstem bronchi between lateral projections. The remainder of the mediastinum and pleural space are normal. No osseous abnormalities are identified. A large, partially pedunculated soft tissue opaque mass is present along the left caudoventral thoracic body wall.

The stomach is largely void of ingesta. The small intestinal tract is normal. The colon contains a moderate amount of semiformed to formed fecal material. The viewable margins of the liver, spleen, urinary bladder, and renal silhouettes are within normal limits. No osseous abnormalities are identified.
Conclusions:
There is no evidence of nodular metastatic pulmonary neoplasia or pneumonia.

1. Dynamic mainstem bronchial collapse, likely due to bronchomalacia.
2. Equivocal cardiomegaly and left atrial enlargement. Given the lack of a cardiac murmur, this finding may be a normal variant.
3. Mixed bronchial and patchy unstructured interstitial patterns. DDx: Age-related changes vs chronic lower airway disease.
4. Unremarkable abdomen.
5. Thoracic body wall mass, consistent with the reported mammary mass.

Findings:
Thorax
Lateral and VD views reported to be acquired on 4/30/2025 are available (2 images). 

There is a relatively large and poorly defined lobular soft tissue opaque mass in the cranial mediastinum causing dorsal and rightward bowing/deviation of the intrathoracic trachea. The caudal margins of this mass abuts and silhouettes with the cardiac silhouette but there is no overt cardiac enlargement. The mid to caudal lung fields are normal; the cranial lung fields are lateral displaced and compressed to some degree by the cranial mediastinal mass. The caudal lobar vessels are normal; the cranial lobar vessels are not visible. The pleural space is normal. The liver is mildly enlarged with rounded margins. There is questionable fluid streaking throughout the abdomen.
Conclusions:
1. Large cranial mediastinal mass. Priority is given to a thymoma; however, other types of neoplasia (e.g. lymphoma, ectopic thyroid carcinoma) cannot be excluded. 
2. There is no overt evidence of pulmonary metastatic disease. 
3. Cranial lung lobe atelectasis secondary to the mass. 
4. Non-specific hepatopathy. Priority is given to a benign process (e.g. vacuolar hepatopathy). 
5. Questionable scant peritoneal effusion. 

Consider consultation with a medical oncologist for further assessment and discussion of potential additional diagnostics and treatment options. Additional diagnostics may included thoracic US with percutaneous tissue sampling of the mass. Abdominal ultrasound and possible tissue/fluid sampling could also be considered.

Findings:
3 View Thoracic Series: 

One of the provided lateral views is not labeled for laterality but is a left lateral view. 
The images are poorly collimated to include the thorax and most of the abdomen in the same view, with decreased technique and motion artifact, all of which decrease the resolution of the finer details of the thorax and increase the amount of image graininess and artifact. This practice should be avoided. 

Motion artifact is present on the VD and left lateral views. A mild, unstructured interstitial to alveolar pattern is centered at the midzone within the left and right caudal lung lobes on the lateral views but improves on the VD views, which tapers ventrally. There is mild, ill-defined soft tissue thickening of the bronchial walls. The cardiac silhouette is mildly to moderately enlarged with loss of the caudal cardiac waist and a moderate left atrial soft tissue bulge. The cardiac silhouette dorsally displaces the intrathoracic trachea and carina on the lateral views. There is at least moderate collapse/compression of the mainstem bronchi at the level of the left atrium, most notable on the left lateral view. The pulmonary vasculature is normal. The mediastinal structures are otherwise unremarkable. No evidence of intrathoracic lymphadenomegaly. A thin pleural fissure line is identified between the right cranial and middle lung lobes on the VD view. 
The visible osseous and extrathoracic soft tissue structures are unremarkable. 
The included abdomen is unremarkable. Metallic hemoclips are identified within the plane of the hepatic silhouette, consistent with a previous surgical procedure such as a cholecystectomy.
Conclusions:
\- Mild pulmonary changes suggestive of mild pneumonia with associated bronchial changes, less likely artifact or mild/early cardiogenic pulmonary edema.  
\- Moderate left-sided cardiomegaly (e.g., mitral valve endocardiosis). 
\- Most likely artifactual/incidental pleural fissure lines (e.g., end-on, fibrosis), less likely scant pleural effusion.  
\- No other abnormalities are noted.

Findings:
**Orthogonal Right Manus Study**: Lateral and DP views are provided. 
The progression of physeal closure suggests an older age than is reported for the patient. 

The carpal joints are normal. 
An acute, complete, closed, well-defined, mildly comminuted fracture is centered at the mid-diaphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 5th digit. A wedge-shaped fracture fragment is at the axial margin of this fracture and is minimally to non-displaced. An oblique fracture line extends from the proximal and abaxial cortical margin of the diaphysis to the distal and axial cortical margin of this proximal phalanx. Extension into the proximal interphalangeal joint of the 5th digit is difficult to determine but is unlikely. Mild circumferential soft tissue swelling is identified surrounding the 5th digit. 
An acute, complete, closed, well-defined long oblique fracture is identified at the proximal phalanx of the 4th digit and extends from the proximal and axial cortical margin to the distal and abaxial cortical margin of this phalanx. Extension into the proximal interphalangeal joint of this digit is difficult to determine but is unlikely. 
The remainder of the viewable osseous and soft tissue structures of the right manus are normal.
Conclusions:
\- Acute, complete, closed, mildly comminuted fracture of the right 5th proximal phalanx with a small wedge-shaped osseous fragment (axial margin) and long oblique fracture of the right 4th proximal phalanx (e.g., unwitnessed trauma, stepped on, traumatic fall). Intra-articular extension of the fracture lines at the right 4th and 5th digits is considered unlikely. 
\- Concurrent soft tissue swelling of the fifth digit (e.g., edema, hemorrhage). 
\- No other abnormalities are noted.

Findings:
2-View Thoracic Series: Referral partner study dated 4/17/25. A left lateral and partial VD view is provided. However, it is suspected that the lateral is a right lateral image. 

A human hand is identified within the plane of the primary beam and is a radiation safety hazard. This practice should be avoided.

The caudal thorax is not included in the VD view, precluding assessment at this level. The patient is rotated to the right in this view with a mild right mediastinal shift of the cardiac silhouette. 
The patient is overweight with moderate subcutaneous fat accumulation. There is a moderate, patchy alveolar pattern throughout the viewable lung fields bilaterally. There is moderate dilation of the proximal left and right caudal mainstem bronchi on the lateral view. A few, indistinct to well-defined, small, soft tissue opaque nodules are within the viewable lung lobes, best noted on the lateral view within the cranial lung lobe at the 5th intercostal space. The right middle lung lobe is reduced in size with rounded margins and homogeneously soft tissue opaque. An indistinct homogeneous soft tissue opacity is superimposed with the cranial cardiac base and proximal aortic arch on the lateral and VD views. The cardiovascular structures and pulmonary vasculature are otherwise normal. The mediastinal structures are normal. No evidence of intrathoracic lymphadenomegaly. Thin pleural fissure lines are noted bilaterally. 
Multifocal incidental spondylosis deformans is identified. A few of the cranial thoracic intervertebral disc spaces are narrowed. Incidental pectus excavatum. The osseous and extrathoracic soft tissue structures are otherwise normal.
There are multiple small curvilinear to granular mineral opacities at the level of the renal silhouettes.
The remainder of the viewable abdomen is normal.
Conclusions:
\- Patchy alveolar to structured/nodular interstitial pulmonary pattern- most likely severe lower airway disease with secondary bronchial mucus plugging and atypical pneumonia (e.g., Mycoplasma). Less likely pulmonary neoplasia of unknown etiology (e.g., metastatic>primary bronchoalveolar carcinoma) or fungal pneumonia (e.g., Histoplasmosis, Blastomycosis). 
\- Likely bronchiectasis, less likely artifact. 
\- Likely artifactual/incidental pleural fissure lines (e.g., secondary to atelectasis, fibrosis), less likely mild pleural effusion, right-sided (e.g., pyothorax, neoplastic, hemorrhage>, chylothorax, FIP).
\- Likely summation artifact at the cranial cardiac base, unlikely a heart-based mass (e.g., metastatic>lymphoma, chemodectoma). 
\- Multifocal IVDD. Unknown clinical significance. 
\- Bilateral nephrolithiasis.
\- No other abnormalities are noted.

Findings:
**Orthogonal Skull, 3-View Thoracic, and 3-View Abdominal Study:** 

**Skull**: VD, RC, right and left lateral views are provided. 
There is mild widening of the periodontal space of the first left and right maxillary and mandibular incisors on the lateral views. The second left and right maxillary incisors are absent. The remainder of the dentition is normal. The left and right tympanic bullae osseous margins are thickened and sclerotic. The osseous and soft tissue structures of the head are normal. No evidence of masses, fractures, or osteolysis. 

**Thorax**: Opposite lateral and VD views are provided. 
The provided thoracic images have an overall grainy appearance, making the assessment of these images difficult and almost non-diagnostic. 

Indistinct, columnar to irregular to well-defined and angular, periosteal proliferation is identified at the cortical margins of the left and right first ribs, most notably at the cranial margins. The medullary cavities of these ribs are irregularly widened distally and narrowed proximally, and variably shaped. The remainder of the viewable osseous and soft tissue structures are normal. There is a region of partially well defined to indistinctly defined soft tissue opacity within the region of the right middle lung lobe and into cranial aspect of the right caudal lung lobe. This is likely partially visible on the right lateral image and visible in the perihilar region or represents additional left lung changes. Many indistinct soft tissue opaque nodules are throughout the lung fields bilaterally. The cardiac silhouette is subjectively normal, however is partially obscured by the pulmonary changes. There is a homogeneous soft tissue opacity within the viewable cranial mediastinal space that is effacing the cranial cardiac silhouette on all views. However, the forelimbs are superimposed with the cranial thorax, hampering the assessment of the cranial mediastinal structures and pleural space. A well-defined, angular, gas opacity is within the plane of the mid esophagus on the lateral views. 

**Abdomen**: Opposite lateral and VD views are provided. 
Abdominal serosal margination is considered adequate. The gastric lumen is moderately dilated with gas. On the left lateral view, the pylorus contains gas. The small intestines, large intestine, and cecum are unable to be followed and contain homogenous to heterogeneous soft tissue material with numerous gas foci throughout this material. The viewable margins of the liver are normal. The margins of the kidneys, spleen, and urinary bladder are unable to be identified. 
Incidental meniscal ossicles. Enthesophytosis of the left patellar tendon is identified on the left lateral view. The osseous and extra-abdominal soft tissue structures are otherwise normal.
Conclusions:
\- Multifocal pulmonary changes likely represents pneumonia with possible abscesses, tracheobronchial lymphadenomegaly and atelectasis. Less likely neoplasia (e.g., metastatic > primary pulmonary neoplasia). Unlikely changes all represent atelectasis.
\- Likely artifactual cranial mediastinal changes (e.g., superimposition/summation, mediastinal fat accumulation), less likely a cranial mediastinal mass (e.g., thymoma) or lymphadenomegaly. 
\- Periosteal changes to the first left and right ribs (e.g., incidental or secondary to previous trauma>hypertrophic osteopathy >>osteomyelitis).
\- Gastric dilation with gas (e.g., aerophagia>gastrointestinal ileus/stasis). 
\- Bilateral thickening of the tympanic bullae (e.g., secondary to chronic otitis media). 
\- Periodontal disease (left and right first maxillary incisors). 
\- Bilateral meniscal ossicles. Unknown clinical significance. 
\- No other abnormalities are noted.

Findings: THORAX/ABDOMEN (opposite lateral, ventrodorsal views, 4 images total): The cranial mediastinum is markedly widened with fat to soft tissue opacity. The intrathoracic trachea is deviated to the right on the ventrodorsal view.  No conclusive cardiomegaly is identified. The remainder of the cardiac silhouette is normal.  The distal trachea and mainstem bronchi are mildly narrowed on both lateral views.  A small conspicuous dorsal tracheal membrane is observed in the cervical region on both lateral views.  There is increased soft tissue opacity dorsal to the mainstem bronchi on lateral views.  The esophagus is minimally distended with gas.  No conclusive pulmonary parenchymal abnormalities are identified.  No abnormalities of the pulmonary vasculature is observed.  No pleural lesions are identified.  No aggressive skeletal lesions are observed.  Numerous small mineral foci are observed in the plane of the liver and a few mineral foci are also observed caudal to the liver in the cranial abdomen.  The spleen and kidneys reveal no conclusive abnormalities.  No conclusive gastrointestinal abnormalities are observed.  The urinary bladder margins are difficult to delineate presuming due to minimal urinary bladder distention and superimposition of intestinal segments.  Abdominal serosal detail is normal.
Conclusions:
Widening of the cranial mediastinum may be an insignificant finding secondary to densely packed mediastinal fat, however, a soft tissue neoplasm (lymphoma, thymoma) in this area is considered equally as likely.  Thoracic ultrasound or thoracic CT would be necessary for more conclusive evaluation.  
Soft tissue opacity dorsal to the carina and mainstem bronchi may suggest tracheobronchial lymphadenopathy or may be artifactual.  CT would be best to further evaluate.  
Mild narrowing of the carina and mainstem bronchi suggest some degree of chondromalacia and this may be exacerbated if tracheobronchial lymph adenopathy is present compressing these airways.
Mineralized foci within the liver presumably associated with the biliary tract and may be incidental or may suggest chronic cholangiohepatitis.  Consider in light of blood work findings.  
Mineral foci just caudal to fluid in the cranial abdomen may represent nonobstructive foreign bodies in the gastrointestinal tract or maybe represent mineralization in the plane of the extrahepatic bile duct or pancreas, potentially representing choliliths and/or pancreatolithiasis.  Ultrasound could be pursued for further evaluation.  Correlation with blood work is recommended to help determine the significance of this finding.

Findings:
3 View Thoracic and Series:

Thorax: 
There are at least six well-defined, round, homogeneously soft tissue opaque nodules within the plane of the caudal lung lobes, most concentrated within the right and left caudal lung lobes extending from the left 6-10th intercostal spaces and the right at the 8-10th intercostal spaces on the VD view and measuring at least one vertebral body in diameter. There is a moderate bronchial pattern throughout the lung fields bilaterally.  The cardiac silhouette is mildly elongated along the apicobasilar axis (VHS ~8.25) with a slight valentine shape on the VD view. The caudal pulmonary arteries are mildly enlarged proximally but taper to normal distally. The mediastinal structures and pleural space are otherwise normal. No evidence of intrathoracic lymphadenomegaly. 
The osseous and extra-thoracic soft tissue structures are normal.

Abdomen: 
The provided series is poorly collimated to include the thorax and abdomen in the same views. This practice should be avoided. 
Abdominal serosal margination is adequate. The gastric lumen is mildly distended with heterogeneous soft tissue and gas opaque material. The small intestines are diffusely small, uniform, and distended with small-volume homogeneous soft tissue material/fluid and multifocal small-volume gas. There is a subjective thickening of the small intestinal walls diffusely, best noted on the VD view. The large intestine is segmentally filled with formed fecal material and gas. The viewable margins of the liver, spleen, and urinary bladder are normal. A few indistinct mineral opacities are within the plane of the left and right renal silhouettes. 
The pelvis is rotated to the left on the VD view with artifactual widening of the right sacroiliac joint. There is a ventral medial luxation of the right femoral head from the acetabular fossa. The remainder of the osseous and extra-abdominal soft tissue structures are otherwise normal. Prominent mamilla are present.
Conclusions:
\- Pulmonary nodules with bronchial changes are suggestive of infectious disease/pneumonia (e.g., fungal >Toxoplasma, parasitic), less likely chronic lower airway disease (e.g., asthma, chronic bronchitis) with secondary mucus plugging, pneumonia, bronchiectasis or abscesses. Pulmonary neoplasia (e.g., carcinoma > lymphoma) cannot be excluded but is considered less likely. 
\- No evidence of congestive heart failure. Mild cardiomegaly (e.g., hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, thyrotoxic). 
\- Right coxofemoral joint luxation. 
\- Subjective small intestinal wall thickening (e.g., severe enteritis, inflammatory bowel disease, gastrointestinal lymphoma). 
\- No evidence of gastrointestinal mechanical obstruction. Likely mild gastric postprandial ingesta and transiting small intestinal digesta/fluid. Less likely foreign material. 
\- Artifact or bilateral nephroliths/mineralized sediment. 
\- No other abnormalities are noted.

Findings:
Provided are two right lateral radiographs of the pelvis with both proximal hind limbs. Images are dated 3/14/25
The more caudally positioned hind leg is assumed to be the right leg.

There is a single cerclage wire of the mid right femur diaphysis with adjacent smooth periosteal thickening. Extending proximocaudally from the level of the cerclage wire is a smooth, curved  and proximally pointed osseous proliferation from the periosteum. There is no lysis surrounding the implant. No fracture line appreciated. 
On the view without exposure through the right stifle there is mild osteophytosis of the patella apex, caudal tibial plateau and possibly the femoral condyles. Summation with other leg hinders evaluation of joint space for effusion. 
There is asymmetry of the coxofemoral joint spaces in which the right leg (presumed as the "down" leg on the table) joint is wider than the other coxofemoral joint and not uniform in its space.
Conclusions:
\-Prior surgical implant placement of right femur with benign smooth remodeling and small osseous proliferation spur. No evidence of current infection or complication involving the implant.
\-Mild degenerative joint disease of the right stifle, possibly from underlying ligament instability.
\-Asymmetry of the hip joint spaces is a little unusual as usually the coxofemoral joint that is further from the plate/table is wider due to magnification and the joint presumed closer to the plate/table should be a little smaller or the same. This appearance of joint asymmetry can happen due to underlying dysplasia and resultant shallow acetabulum or subluxation. 

An exact cause for the lameness is not confidently identified. Referral to an orthopedic surgeon could be considered. Orthogonal radiographs with collimation to the pelvis/hips and orthogonal radiographs collimated to right stifle could be considered for a closer evaluation of the right coxofemoral and stifle joints.

Findings:
Provided are 3 images for interpretation: Right lateral thorax and proximal right forelimb, left lateral thorax, and ventrodorsal thorax. Images acquired March 24, 2025. 

There is irregular to smooth periosteal proliferation centered at the caudal aspect of the proximal humerus. On the left lateral view, following various grayscale windowing of the image, the periosteal proliferation appears more columnar. Only on the right lateral view is there suspect very mild permeative lysis of the proximal right humeral metaphysis.
Throughout the thorax there are multiple well-defined variably sized but overall small to tiny mineral opaque nodules. There are no discrete soft tissue opaque nodules appreciated. The cardiovascular structures are normal. No evidence of intrathoracic lymphadenopathy.
Conclusions:
\-The lesion of the proximal right humerus has subtle but present aggressive characteristics. Most likely differential is a primary bone tumor, such as osteosarcoma or histiocytic sarcoma (given the breed). Osteomyelitis from bacteria or fungus, or remodeling changes secondary to an unknown trauma, are not entirely ruled out but considered much less likely. Referral to an orthopedic surgeon for biopsy could be considered for further evaluation.
-The presence of multiple mineralized nodules are supportive of benign osteomas/osseous metaplasia, however, they admittedly confound evaluation for metastatic disease. Occasionally osteosarcoma metastatic nodules are mineralized, but that is rather uncommon and at this time benign osteomas are considered more likely. Continued radiographic monitoring of the thorax with three-view thoracic radiographs compared over time to prior studies is recommended, or CT of the thorax for more sensitive evaluation for metastatic nodules.

There is a suspect small alveolar pattern cranioventrally, better seen on the right lateral view, dorsal to the 2nd-3rd sternebrae. There is multifocal mild to moderate spondylosis deformans of the thoracic spine, most severe at T2-T3.
Conclusions:
\-The pulmonary pattern combined with cardiomegaly and likely vascular congestion is most concerning for cardiogenic edema secondary to heart failure. An interstitial pneumonia or severe lower airway inflammatory disease are considered less likely. Diuretic trial and repeat radiographs could be considered as well as referral to cardiologist for echocardiogram.
-Cardiomegaly is supportive of underlying heart disease; dilated cardiomyopathy is prioritized based on breed.
-Chronic intervertebral disc disease and secondary degenerative changes to the spine.
-Mineral opacity seen only on the right lateral view over the caudal dorsal thorax is likely summation artifact with debris or plate/detector artifact.

Findings:
**Orthogonal Right Antebrachial and 3-View Thoracic Study:** 

_Right Antebrachium_: Lateral and CrCd views are provided. 
Marked moth-eaten to expansile osteolysis is centered within the medullary cavity at the mid-diaphysis of the ulna with an indistinct zone of transition proximally and distally. There is marked moth-eaten cortical lysis of the ulna with moderate, wispy to columnar, indistinct periosteal proliferation at this level. This osteolysis extends proximally to the proximal diaphysis and distally to the distal diaphysis. There is moderate regional soft tissue swelling centered at this level (mid-caudolateral margin of the antebrachium). Wispy mineral opaque striations are noted within this regional soft tissue swelling. No evidence of intra-articular extension into the cubital or antebrachiocarpal joints. The remainder of the viewable osseous and soft tissue structures are normal. 

_Thorax_: Opposite lateral and VD views are provided. 
There is a mild bronchial pattern throughout the lung fields bilaterally and is considered a normal conspicuous/age-related pulmonary background for this patient. The pulmonary parenchyma is normal. The cardiac silhouette is normal to mildly enlarged with a mild left atrial soft tissue bulge. The pulmonary vasculature is normal. The mediastinal structures and pleural space are normal. No evidence of intrathoracic lymphadenomegaly. 
The osseous and extrathoracic soft tissue structures are normal. Multiple metallic opaque foci are within the superficial soft tissues of the dorsal thorax and right proximal forelimb, considered an external artifact. 
The spleen is subjectively mildly enlarged on the right lateral view.
Conclusions:
\- Most likely primary osseous neoplasia, right ulna, (e.g., osteosarcoma> chondrosarcoma, hemangiosarcoma) with regional soft tissue extension and/or edema. Less likely metastatic lesion, primary soft tissue neoplasia (e.g., soft tissue sarcoma) with intraosseous extension, or osteomyelitis (e.g., fungal>bacterial). 
\- No evidence of pulmonary metastatic disease. 
\- Likely a normal variation, less likely mild cardiomegaly (e.g., mitral valve endocardiosis).
\- Splenomegaly is likely normal variation or benign etiology, less likely round cell neoplasia.  
\- No other abnormalities are noted.

Findings:
Thorax
A single right lateral views dated 3/4/2025 is available (1 digital image). 

The pulmonary parenchyma, cardiovascular structures, pleural space and mediastinum are normal. The included osseous structures are normal. 

Abdomen 
Right lateral and VD views dated 3/4/2025 are available (3 digital images). 

There is normal serosal margin detail throughout the abdomen. The liver is mildly enlarged extending beyond the costal arch; however, the liver maintains sharp margination. The stomach is mildly distended with variably-sized soft tissue opaque rectangular to cylindrical structures. Some of the smaller structures in the stomach are intermediate soft tissue to mineral opacity. Similar content is present in the intestinal tract, suspected colon in additional to presumptive normal fecal material. The kidneys are obscured by overlying intestine. The remaining intra-abdominal structures are normal. There is an incidental finding of multifocal spondylosis deformans in the included portions of the spine. An ovoid soft tissue nodular opacity is superimposed on the mid ventral abdomen and spleen. There is the impression of degenerative joint disease of the right coxofemoral joint; however, this joint is not fully included in the field of view.
Conclusions:
1. Gastrointestinal content is suspected to represent normal ingesta. The small intermediate opacity material may represent partially digested kibble; however, transiting currently non-obstructive foreign material cannot be excluded. There is no evidence of gastrointestinal obstruction. 
2. Mild hepatomegaly. Priority is given to a benign hepatopathy (e.g. vacuolar hepatopathy, nodular regeneration). 
3. Normal thorax based on a single projection. 
4. Suspected right coxofemoral DJD. 
5. Nodular opacity superimposed on the mid ventral abdomen and spleen on the lateral view is most consistent with a superimposed cutaneous lesion; however, the possibility of a small splenic lesion cannot be completely excluded. 

Consider repeat abdominal radiographs after a period of fasting to further assess the gastrointestinal content. Abdominal ultrasound with possible tissue sampling could be considered to further assess the hepatopathy.

Findings:
Three view orthogonal images of the thorax (5 images total) are evaluated:

There is a mixed diffuse unstructured interstitial and bronchial pulmonary pattern. On one of the VD images, there is a mild leftward mediastinal shift with volume reduction and increased soft tissue opacity of the left lung.  This does not persist on other images, consistent with pulmonary atelectasis.  The lungs are variably mildly hypoinflated on the lateral images. The cardiovascular structures and pleural space are normal. The liver is mildly enlarged with rounded margins.  The abdomen is mildly pendulous.  The patient is over conditioned. The skeletal structures are normal.
Conclusions:
1.  Mild, diffuse pulmonary infiltrates are most consistent with chronic lower airway inflammation (e.g., inflammatory, infectious, allergic, or irritant) and/or age-related change.  There is no evidence of pulmonary edema. 
2.  Normal cardiovascular structures without evidence of heart failure. 
3.  Mild nonspecific hepatopathy.

The aforementioned findings are mild and may or may not explain the reported clinical signs.  If the patient is not responding to empirical therapies for bronchitis, lower airway wash could provide more information.  An abdominal ultrasound could also be considered.

Findings:
THORAX (opposite lateral, ventrodorsal views, 4 images total): An ovoid soft tissue opaque mass is present in the perihilar aspect of the lungs near midline.  Is difficult to determine if this mass is in the left or right lung as the ventrodorsal view is significantly obliqued.  A more faint but similar sized ovoid soft tissue opacity is observed in the plane of the heart base and distal trachea/carina without conclusively deviating the mainstem bronchi or trachea.  This lesion is difficult to delineate on the ventrodorsal views.  There is increased soft tissue opacity and decreased volume of the right cranial lung lobe with deviation of the cardiac silhouette to the right on the ventrodorsal view.  There is a moderate diffuse bronchial pulmonary pattern throughout all lung fields.  No cardiac enlargement is identified and the pulmonary vessels are normal.  No conclusive pleural lesions are identified.

ABDOMEN (opposite lateral, ventrodorsal views, 3 images total): The stomach is mildly to moderately distended with fluid and granular soft tissue opaque material as well as a few minute mineral opacities.  All small intestinal segments are normal in size, most being moderately distended with fluid and gas.  The colon is mildly distended with semiformed fecal material proximally and semi-formed fecal material distally.  The liver, spleen, kidneys, and urinary bladder are normal.  Abdominal serosal detail is normal.
Conclusions:
*   Perihilar pulmonary mass highly suggestive of pulmonary malignancy.  The possibly this mass represents a nonmalignant etiology such as a pulmonary granuloma is plausible but considered less likely.
*   Soft tissue opacity in the plane of the heart base may may represent a second pulmonary mass in this region, may represent tracheobronchial lymphadenopathy, or represent an artifact. CT of the thorax is highly recommended for more conclusive evaluation. 
*   Diffuse moderate bronchial pattern may suggest feline asthma or less likely infectious in the inflammatory disease, particularly if the mass represents a granulomatous lesion. 
*   Atelectasis and/or infitlrate (inflammatory, malignant) in the right cranial lung lobe.
*   Granular mineral opaque content in the stomach is likely insignificant.  Otherwise normal abdomen.

**PLEASE SEE IMPORTANT MESSAGE AT BOTTOM OF REPORT REGARDING FUTURE RADIOGRAPH CONSULTATIONS.**

Provided are right lateral and ventrodorsal radiographs of the thorax and abdomen, 4 images total. The study is dated February 26, 2025.

Thorax: There is moderate general enlargement of the cardiac silhouette with dorsal displacement of the caudal trachea/carina and more focal marked left atrial enlargement and protrusion in the area of the left auricle. The cranial pulmonary vein appears mildly enlarged/congested compared to its respective artery on the lateral view. There is a mild to moderate caudodorsal unstructured interstitial pattern, more severe left sided on the VD view. On the lateral view, at the level of the costochondral junctions, there is a conspicuous line of soft tissue opacity that extends cranial to caudal over the ventral thorax, with fat opacity and conspicuity of the cardiac silhouette apex ventral to the soft tissue margin/line. There is an ovoid soft tissue opaque to questionably faintly mineral opaque subcutaneous mass (6.2cm x 3.5cm) of the dorsal soft tissues, superimposed with the spinous processes. This mass very likely correlates with an ill-defined ovoid opacity over the left caudal thoracic wall on the VD view. There are 2-3 broad-based fat opaque subcutaneous protrusions along the ventral thorax, largest at the level of the xiphoid process.

Abdomen: The serosal detail is normal. The stomach contains a small amount of gas. Only on the ventrodorsal view, there is a rounded soft tissue opacity (2.5cm x 3.2cm) superimposed with the gastric lumen, to the left of the spine. Small intestines are normal in diameter, distribution, and content. Colon diffusely contains fecal material. The visible margins of liver, spleen, kidneys, and urinary bladder are normal.
Conclusions:
\- The moderate to severe left cardiomegaly combined with mild pulmonary venous congestion and caudodorsal interstitial pattern, is most concerning for mild cardiogenic edema secondary to left-sided heart failure. Diuretic trial and repeat radiographs could be considered to monitor for resolution of the caudodorsal pulmonary pattern. Also, referral for echocardiogram could be performed to better characterize heart disease and function.
\-The ventral margin of soft tissue opacity on the thoracic lateral view at the level of the costochondral junctions is an incidental summation artifact with the pleura and angle of the thorax at this level.
\-Nonspecific dorsal subcutaneous mass that is not confidently fat opaque so could represent benign or malignant etiologies. Correlate to tissue sampling.
\-Small subcutaneous adipose masses, likely benign lipomas.
\-The rounded soft tissue opacity seen superimposed with the stomach on only the ventrodorsal view could be within the gastric lumen (intentional food or foreign body), but considered more likely incidental given the lack of any vomiting or anorexia. If gastrointestinal signs develop then repeat abdominal imaging with the inclusion of the left lateral view could be performed (left lateral views can sometimes help get gas within the plane of the pyloric antrum and better highlight luminal contents).

Findings:
An extended leg VD of the pelvis and a lateral image of one of the stifles is evaluated (2 images total).  The lateral image of the stifle is unlabeled.  Radiographic technique (overexposure) partially precludes evaluation of the stifle joint space and regional soft tissues on the lateral image.

Bilaterally, there is reduced coverage of the femoral heads by the acetabulae.  The femoral heads and necks are widened with circumferential osteophytes/enthesophytes.  A small osteophyte/enthesophyte is also along the right cranial acetabular margin.

On the VD image.  There is external rotation of the stifles, secondary to patient positioning. The patellas are normally positioned.   Bilaterally, there are multifocal rounded mineral foci in the expected location of the lateral fabellae with wispy mineral in the surrounding soft tissues.

On the lateral stifle image, there is the impression of increased space between the patella and the trochlear ridge, attributed to positioning, with several small rounded to angular mineral foci in the plane of the cranial aspect of the joint. There is the impression of a mild concave lucency along the articular surface of one of the femoral condyles; however, this is not corroborated on the VD image.

The gluteal and pelvic limb muscles are normal and symmetric. The included portion of the lumbar spine and tarsi are normal.
Conclusions:
1.  Bilateral lateral fabellae change may be attributed to congenital multipartite fabellae or less likely, some sort of musculotendinopathy affecting the lateral head of the gastrocnemius. Abnormalities of the fabellae can be associated with medial patellar luxation and to a lesser extent, cranial cruciate ligament injury, although neither of these things are captured on the provided images. 
2.  Stifle osteochondromas or less likely, osteochondritis dissecans, laterality unknown. 
3.  Mild bilateral coxofemoral degenerative joint disease, secondary to hip dysplasia.

A surgical consultation could provide more information and guide therapies if the patient has clinical signs.

Serial abdominal radiographs after implementing supportive care could help track the passage. Alternatively, an abdominal ultrasound could provide more information.

Findings:
Thorax
Opposite lateral and VD views dated 2/17/2025 are compared to a study dated 11/29/2024 (a total of 6 digital images). Variations in radiographic techniques and post-processing algorithms between studies hinders comparison to some degree. 

11/29/2024 Study Findings: 

There is a questionable diffuse bronchial pulmonary pattern. The cardiovascular structures are normal. On the right lateral view, there is increased soft tissue opacity in the mid ventral thorax partially overlying the cardiac silhouette with a slight angular/triangular margin cranially; however, margination of the cardiac silhouette is maintained. There is questionable tenting of the diaphragm. 

2/17/2025 Study Findings: 

There is a more distinct bronchial pulmonary pattern compared to the previous but this bronchial pulmonary pattern is only considered mild at this time. A few minute nodular soft tissue opacities are noted throughout the lungs. On the VD view, there is mild widening of the caudal mediastinal reflection due to incidental fat deposition causing a band-like to triangular opacity in this region. The cardiovascular structures. There is a small triangular soft tissue opacity in the mid ventral lung field on the right lateral view, just cranial to the cardiac silhouette. The band of increased soft tissue overlying the cardiac silhouette noted on this view in the previous study is no longer present. Questionable diaphragmatic tenting is again noted on the VD view.
Conclusions:
1. Mild diffuse bronchial pulmonary pattern with persistent questionable diaphragmatic tenting is most consistent with inflammatory lower airway disease (e.g. feline asthma). This pattern is more distinct than previous which could be due to variations in radiographic technique and post-processing algorithms; however, true progression of disease cannot be excluded. 
2. The minute nodular soft tissue opacities noted in today's study are most compatible with mucus filled terminal bronchi, minute broncholiths and/or incidental pulmonary osteomas. The size of these lesions is not consistent with metastatic disease. 
3. There is no evidence of overt cardiovascular disease in either study. Additionally, there is no evidence of CHF in either study. 
4. The increased soft tissue opacity in the mid ventral lung field noted on the right lateral views in both studies (extent of this opacity varies between studies) is most compatible with incidental mediastinal fat deposition and transient focal atelectasis. There is no conclusive pleural effusion in either study (the appearance of the right mid ventral lung field on the 11/29/2024 is considered to be an example of pseudo-pleural effusion). Mediastinal fat deposits can be present even in patients not considered visibly overweight. 

 
Thank you for your referral of this case for radiographic interpretation. Please contact me via email (chase.constant@medvet.com) if you have any questions or concerns related to this report. Be advised that I typically work Tuesday-Friday and emails received outside of these days may result in a delayed response.

Findings:
Thorax
Opposite lateral and VD views dated 2/17/2025 (3 images) are available. 

There is mixed severe unstructured interstitial and alveolar pattern throughout the lungs, most severe in the right cranial and left caudal lung lobes. There is the impression of multiple ill-defined small pulmonary nodules in several lung lobes. The cardiovascular structures are normal. The pleural space and mediastinum are normal. The included portions of the abdomen and musculoskeletal structures are normal.
Conclusions:
Mixed severe and diffuse pulmonary disease is a non-specific finding; however, given the patient's signalment and impression of concurrent nodular interstitial component, priority is given to metastatic lung disease with possible concurrent pneumonitis and/or pulmonary hemorrhage. Fungal disease should also be considered (e.g. blastomycosis, histoplasmosis). Bacterial pneumonia and inflammatory lung disease (e.g. bronchitis) are considered less likely at this time.

Fungal urine antigen testing could be considered to exclude this differential. 
 
Thank you for your referral of this case for radiographic interpretation. Please contact me via email (chase.constant@medvet.com) if you have any questions or concerns related to this report. Findings:
2-View Thoracic/Abdomen Radiographic Study: The R marker is incorrectly labeled on the left side of the patient on the VD image. The rotation of the patient, movement artifact, and poor collimation of the radiographs, including the thorax and abdomen, decrease the resolution of the finer details of the thorax and increase the amount of image graininess and artifact. This practice should be avoided. Consider collimated radiographs only to include the thorax, which may be helpful to better assess for pulmonary changes. 

There is marked dorsal angulation of the mid to caudal sternum, causing marked rotation of the cardiac silhouette to the left side and decreased volume of the left cranial lung lobe. Subjectively, the cardiac silhouette is enlarged. There is moderate diffuse ill-defined soft tissue thickening of the bronchial walls, and the right middle lung lobe is markedly collapsed, triangular in shape, and diffusely soft tissue opaque. Cardiovascular structures and pulmonary parenchyma cannot be accurately assessed. 
Pleural space and mediastinum are within normal limits.
No abdominal organomegaly.
A moderate amount of heterogeneous soft tissue material is present within the stomach. The small intestines are multifocally moderately dilated with homogeneous soft tissue opacity and gas with no evidence of two populations of the bowel. The large intestine is multifocally filled with heterogeneous fecal material and gas.
The liver, splenic, renal, and serosal margins are normal.
There are multiple small ovoid-rimmed mineral opaque structures in the cranial peritoneal space and thoracic pleural space.
There is osteophytosis of the coxofemoral joints bilaterally.
Conclusions:
Chronic lower airway disease (e.g., asthma, chronic bronchitis) with right middle lung lobe collapse.
Pectus excavatum, likely congenital, less likely secondary to chronic airway disease. Secondary mediastinal shift to the left with left cranial lung atelectasis, less likely true pulmonary disease. Additional lung/thoracic disease cannot be ruled out. 
Cardiomegaly (such as hypertrophic cardiomyopathy or artifact) with no evidence of cardiogenic pulmonary edema. 
Likely postprandial gastric ingesta, less likely nonobstructive gastric foreign material, with aerophagia causing intestinal dilation. 
Likely incidental pleural and peritoneal Bate's bodies.
Bilateral coxarthrosis.

Findings:
Provided are four DICOMs for interpretation: two laterals of the left forelimb, a combined distal forelimb dorsopalmar radiograph, and a lateral of the right mid forelimb. 

Patient skeleton is noted to have an overall chondrodystrophic conformation. 
The ulnae bilaterally are shortened. The left ulna distal physis has some mild smooth osseous proliferation of its cranial aspect, ill-defined irregular margins and adjacent mild sclerosis. Visible right distal ulnar metaphysis is normal. On the bilateral forelimb DP view there is a more conspicuous lucent line through the distolateral cortex of the left ulna, proximal to the more well-defined physis. Additionally, on this DP view, there is very mild lateral bowing of the distal left ulna, and equivocal lateral bowing of the right ulna. 
On lateral views of the left forelimb there is mild cranial bowing of the distal left radius. There is medial curvature of the distal radii and impression of valgus bilaterally (though limbs not quite positioned to optimally evaluate this). 
There is mild widening of the humeroulnar joint compared to the humeroradial joint on the lateral view of the right forelimb. On the left forelimb lateral views, the proximal trochlear notch and part of the humeroulnar joint is somewhat obscured and summating with the humeral condyle, but incongruency is suspected.
Shoulders are unremarkalbe.
Conclusions:
\- Overall the patient has evidence of bilateral angular limb deformity (ALD) that is worse on the left and there is some remodeling change to the left distal ulnar physis suggestive that it may have undergone some mild trauma which may explain the worsened curvature of this limb and lameness. The lateralized linear lucency on the DP view proximal to the distal left ulna physis is likely a portion of the physis that is widened and visualized at this angle due to its oblique orientation in the cranial-to-caudal plane, less likely a fracture fissure. 
\- Likely bilateral elbow incongruency. 

Referral to an orthopedic specialist may be considered. They may perform serial radiographic monitoring as physeal remodeling and ultimate degree of ALD can take time to reveal itself following microtrauma.

Findings:
Nine images of the antebrachi are evaluated.  In the majority of images, evaluation of the soft tissue structures is hindered due to radiographic technique (over-exposure).

There is very subtle thickening of the soft tissues along the dorsodistal aspect of the left radius. The other osseous and soft tissue structures are normal, including the long bones, physes, and joints.
Conclusions:
1.  Mild left distal radial swelling (edema, hemorrhage, or cellulitis).  No fractures or luxations are identified.
2.  Normal right antebrachium.

Thank you for your submission.  There is no indication for surgery based on the provided images.  The curvilinear lines in the plane of the left distal radial metaphysis on some images likely represent the superimposition of the normal curvature of the bone.  With that being said, radiographically inapparent physeal trauma could still exist. If the patient is not responding to medical management, repeat radiographs could help assess for trauma-related premature physeal closure and angular limb deformity.  If this occurs, an orthopedic consultation could be beneficial.

Findings:
Multiple orthogonal radiographs of the forelimbs are available for interpretation (7 images total), dated February 13, 2025. This includes orthogonal images of both manus/carpi and lateral views of the left elbow and shoulder. 

Left carpus/manus: There is mild intracapsular swelling of the antebrachiocarpal joint. Best seen on images #2 and #6 there is mild cranial/dorsal osseous proliferation at the distal radius articular margin and radial carpal bone. There is mild osseous proliferation of the accessory carpal bone distal margin. On the DP view of left manus (image #1) there is moderate smooth to irregular osseous proliferation at the region of distal 5th metacarpal joint and superimposed palmar sesamoid bones, based on the lateral image of the carpus (image #2) this suspected to be primarily associated with the sesamoid bones. 

Right carpus/manus: There is mild osseous proliferation of the accessory carpal bone distal margin. Better seen on the collimated DP view of right carpus (image #4) there is a small lip curved osseous proliferation extending from the distomedial radial groove. There is mild smooth to irregular osseous proliferation at the summating margins of the distolateral tubercle of the 5th metacarpal bone and lateral sesamoid bone. 

Left elbow: No abnormalities. 

Left shoulder: No abnormalities.

No abnormalities of the included neck and thorax.
Conclusions:
\- Left antebrachiocarpal mild degenerative joint disease with evidence of mild joint effusion and/or joint capsule thickening. An underlying septic arthritis cannot entirely be ruled out but is less likely due to the mild degree of swelling. Arthrocentesis with cytology and culture could be considered for further evaluation. 
\- Bilateral mild accessory carpal enthesopathy. 
\- Bilateral 5th digit mild to moderate collateral ligament enthesopathy and/or lateral sesamoiditis. 
\- Right mild abductor pollicis longus tenosynovitis.

Findings:
Two view orthogonal images of the abdomen are evaluated and compared to images from 2/1/2024 (Clario, MRN: 1094160).  The cranial abdomen is incompletely imaged on both views.  Radiographic technique partially hinders evaluation. 

Renal margins are indistinct, attributed to radiographic technique.   A cluster of small opaque mineral structures remains in the plane of the peridiverticular region of the right kidney with an elongated mineral opaque structure similarly in the plane of the right ureter. The urinary bladder remains small and homogeneously soft tissue/fluid opaque. There is now mineral opaque medical tubing consistent with a ureteral stent in the right retroperitoneum.  The cranial and caudal aspects of the catheter have a pigtail configuration and are positioned in the expected location of the right renal pelvis and urinary bladder, respectively. The stent appears normal, without kinks.  The abdominal serosal detail remains normal. The gastrointestinal tract remains normal in size and content. The liver and spleen remain normal.  The musculoskeletal structures and caudal thorax remain normal.
Conclusions:
*   Similar right nephrolithiasis/ureterolithiasis with newly identified ureteral stent placement. Otherwise, normal abdomen.

Radiographically, there are no concerns with stent placement, though if clinical suspicion persists, sonography is recommended to evaluate the urogenital tract more closely.  There are no other abnormalities to explain the reported clinical signs.

Findings:
Three images (a lateral and two ventrodorsal) of the skull are evaluated:

On the second VD image, there is the impression of mildly increased soft tissue opacity in the plane of the right caudal nasal cavity; however, the image is rotated and findings are not corroborated on the other two views.  The nasal turbinates remain distinct. There is no mass effect or deviation of the nasal septum. The cribriform plate appears intact. The frontal sinuses and temporomandibular joints are normal. The other osseous and soft tissue structures are normal.
Conclusions:
Normal skull.  A definitive cause for the reported clinical signs is not evident. The appearance of the right caudal nasal on the second VD image is not repeatable and most likely attributed to obliquity.

Thank-you for the good quality skull radiographs.  If the patient is not responding to medical management, an internal medicine referral could be considered.

Findings:
Orthogonal images of the thorax are available for interpretation (3 total).

Evaluation of the cranial mediastinum and cranioventral lung lobes is limited by superimposition of the elbows. No pulmonary consolidation is identified. There is a single small mineral opaque nodule at the right caudal lung lobe. No soft tissue opaque pulmonary nodules are identified. The cardiac silhouette is normal in size with increased sternal contact, considered an incidental age-related change. The pulmonary vasculature is normal in diameter. The pleural space is unremarkable. No cranial mediastinal widening is identified on the ventrodorsal image. There is multifocal thoracic intervertebral disc space narrowing and spondylosis deformans.
Conclusions:
*   Small mineralized pulmonary nodule, most consistent with a granuloma or broncholith. 
*   A specific etiology for the reported cough is not identified. Inflammatory airway disease (e.g. asthma) is not excluded).

Findings:
2-View Thoracic/Abdomen Radiographic Study: There is an ungloved human finger in the primary beam, which is a radiation safety hazard. The patient is rotated on both images, hampering evaluation. 

Cardiovascular structures are normal. 
There are numerous variably sized round, well-defined soft tissue pulmonary nodules to small masses throughout the lung fields bilaterally, and multiple contain central gas cavitations. 
Pleural space and mediastinum are within normal limits.
A moderate amount of heterogeneous soft tissue material is present within the stomach.  The small intestines are multifocally mildly filled with homogeneous soft tissue opacity and mild gas with no evidence of two populations of the bowel. The large intestine is multifocally filled with heterogeneous fecal material and gas.
The liver, splenic, renal, and serosal margins are normal.
The caudoventral urinary bladder to cranial urethral margins is undulating, giving the impression of luminal dilation/thickening.
There is mild mineral opacity in the plane of the sublumbar lymph nodes and possible mild osseous proliferation at the ventral margins of L6 and L7 vertebral bodies.
Conclusions:
Extensive metastatic pulmonary neoplasia (e.g., carcinoma > other). Unlikely fungal granulomas. 
Urinary bladder/urethral changes are suggestive of neoplasia (e.g., TCC), less likely artifact.
Artifact from rotation or metastatic sublumbar lymph nodes and lumbar vertebral bodies.

Findings: BILATERAL CARPI (dorsal palmar, lateral views, 2 images total): The entire right manus is included on both images but the entirety of the left manus is only included on the dorsopalmar view.  There is severe intra and extracapsular soft tissue swelling at the left carpus.  The left carpal bones appear slightly smaller and slightly more irregular with less defined margins than their counterparts on the left, particularly on the lateral views.  A deeper than normal radiolucent medial radial sulcus is noted at the distal medial aspect of each radius and an abnormal extension of bony proliferation medial and slightly cranial to the distal radius is observed extending from the radial sulcus bilaterally; these findings are highly indicative of stenosing tenosynovitis of the abductor policus longus muscles bilaterally. The bony proliferation is more extensive on the left than the right, particularly aong the cranial margin of the distal radius, which is markedly irregular. There is also mild extracapsular soft tissue swelling medial to radial sulcus and bony proliferation on the right thoracic limb, suggesting swelling of the tendon sheath.  The diffuse soft tissue swelling at the left radius likely obscures swelling in the tendon sheath of the left abductor policus longus tendon. The remainder of the study is normal.
Conclusions:
*   Bilateral stenosing tenosynovitis of the abductor pollicis longus muscles.  This disease appears to be more advanced on the left.  
*   Concurrent diffuse intracapsular and extracapsular soft tissue swelling of the left carpus and slight irregularity and slightly poor margination of the left carpal bones may suggest a septic arthritis and/or minimally erosive immune-mediated arthritis. Repeative trauma (from walking/running on the limb or from excessive liking/self-mutilation) resulting in the soft tissue swelling at the left carpus is also possible. Early soft tissue/joint-associated malignancy is considered unlikely at this time. Arthrocentesis is recommended for cytology, fluid analysis, and culture. Synovial biopsy for histopatholgy may also help in the work up of this patient. 
*   Consultation with an orthopedist is recommended.

Findings:
Two orthogonal images of the thorax and abdomen dated 2/6/2025 are evaluated:

Thorax:
The cardiac silhouette is severely enlarged and globoid containing a mixture of fat and lobular soft tissue opacity.  The caudal margin of the cardiac silhouette is poorly distinguished from the diaphragm on both images. The caudal mediastinum is widened. On the VD image, the right cranial and right middle lung lobes are homogeneously soft tissue opaque and reduced in volume, and the left lung is mildly hyperinflated, crossing midline.  Otherwise, there is a mild diffuse bronchial pulmonary pattern.  

Abdomen
There is reduced hepatic volume within the abdomen with the impression of lobular soft tissue crossing the diaphragm into the caudal thorax.  There is mild cranial displacement of the stomach, though the gastric axis remains normal.  The gastrointestinal tract is otherwise normal in size and content.  The right kidney is also cranially displaced. The spleen is normally positioned in the left cranial abdomen on the VD.  The urinary bladder is normal.  The abdominal serosal detail is normal.  Multiple of the caudal thoracic and lumbar intervertebral disc spaces contain ovoid mineral centrally.  Incidentally, there is mild lumbar and lumbosacral spondylosis deformans.
Conclusions:
1.  Peritoneopericardial diaphragmatic hernia (PPDH), likely containing falciform fat, liver, and gallbladder.  No evidence of bowel entrappment/incarceration.  
2.  Mild chronic lower airway inflammation, commonly of allergic origin (e.g., asthma).
3.  Right cranial and middle lung lobe atelectasis, consider sedation/recumbence-induced or resorptive, as a sequelae to chronic lower airway inflammation (e.g., mucous plugging).
4.  Multifocal thoracolumbar mineralized intervertebral discs, *in situ*.

Findings:
Right lateral and VD images of the abdomen dated 2/6/2025 are evaluated (four images total). 

The abdominal serosal detail is normal. The stomach is normal in size and contains a moderate volume of heterogeneous soft tissue. The small intestines are normal in size and content, containing mostly gas and some homogeneous soft tissue/fluid. The cecum and colon contain a small volume of partially formed feces and gas. The liver and visible renal margins are normal.  The spleen is diffusely enlarged with sharp margins. The urinary bladder is not well seen due to visceral crowding.  The caudal thorax and musculoskeletal structures are normal.
Conclusions:
1.  Normal abdomen without gastrointestinal foreign material or mechanical obstruction. The gastric content most likely represents normal ingesta.
2.  Colonic content is consistent with reported soft stool.
3.  Splenomegaly is likely a variant of normal for this breed.  The splenic tail is what creates the triangular soft tissue opacity in the right mid abdomen on the VD image. 

A cause for the reported clinical signs is not identified. Non-radiographically evident gastroenteritis or pancreatitis remain possible causes. If signs persist despite medical management, an abdominal ultrasound could be considered.

Findings:
Two orthogonal images of the thorax dated November 21, 2024 are compared to 3 orthogonal images of the thorax dated February 3, 2025 (5 images total).

The cardiovascular structures, pleural space, and mediastinum remain normal.  The trachea and principal bronchi remain normal without collapsse.  The remains of very mild diffuse bronchointerstitial pulmonary pattern.  There are again several bulbous, remodeled, mineralized costochondral junctions, considered benign degenerative change. The liver remains mildly enlarged.  A couple punctate to curvilinear mineral and metallic foci are variably in the plane of the peritoneum on the lateral images, that are not corroborated on the VD image (previously not image), suspected to represent external debris.  The other soft tissue and osseous structures remain normal.
Conclusions:
1.  Mild chronic bronchitis and/or age-related change.  This may or may not explain the reported coughing.
2.  The cardiovascular structures are radiographically normal without evidence of congestive heart failure.  This does not exclude underlying cardiac disease, so if there remains clinical suspicion for such, an echocardiogram could provide more information.
3.  Nonspecific hepatopathy.

Findings:
Three view orthogonal images of the thorax are evaluated:

The cardiac sillhouette (VHS 8 v) and pulmonary vessels are normal.  The pleural space and mediastinum are normal. There is a mild diffuse bronchial pulmonary pattern. The included abdomen and musculoskeletal structures are normal.
Conclusions:
1.  Mild diffuse airway thickening supports chronic lower airway inflammation, commonly of allergic origin (e.g., asthma). Infectious, inflammatory, or irritant etiologies are also possible. 
2.  Normal juvenile cardiovascular structures without evidence of congestive heart failure.

Findings:
BILATERAL THORACIC LIMBS (lateral, craniocaudal views, 4 images total): The medial coronoid processes of both ulna is are markedly abnormal in shape, with the medial coronoid process of the left ulna being markedly elongated and cuboidal while the medial coronoid process of the right ulna is markedly crescent shaped and elongated.  Mild irregularity along the medial aspect of the trochlea of the left humeral condyle is noted opposite the abnormal left medial coronoid process.  The appearance of the distal metaphyses and diaphyses of the left and right ulnas is is not considered to be outside the bounds of normal variation for the age of the patient.  No soft tissue swelling is observed surrounding these portions of the limbs or elsewhere in the field-of-view.  No conclusive angular limb deformities are identified.

THORAX (ventrodorsal view, 1 image total): The cardiac and pulmonary vessels are normal.  There is a hazy unstructured interstitial pulmonary pattern throughout all lung fields that is believed to be secondary to radiographic technique and algorithm.  No conclusive pulmonary parenchymal lesions are observed.  A remnant thymus is observed in the cranial thorax.  No intrathoracic lymphadenopathy or pleural lesions are identified.  No abnormalities of the skeletal or extrathoracic structures are noted within the field-of-view.
Conclusions:
*   Severe bilateral medial coronoid disease/elbow dysplasia with resultant secondary osteophytosis/degenerative joint disease of the left elbow.  Given that the medial coronoid disease is radiographically more severe on the left, it makes sense that the patient is limping on the left thoracic limb.  Consultation with an orthopedist to discuss tried treatment options is recommended. 
*   The appearance of the distal ulnas and distal radii is considered to be within normal limits for the age of the patient and there is no conclusive evidence to suggest hypertrophic osteodystrophy at this time, however, repeat radiography in the future is recommended if there continues to be clinical suspicion of hypertrophic osteodystrophy.
*   Normal thorax on single ventrodorsal view.

Findings:
2-View Thoracic Radiographic Study: The images are not labeled for laterality and include a right lateral and VD image.

Cardiovascular structures and pulmonary parenchyma are normal.
No metastatic disease or pneumonia. 
Pleural space and mediastinum are within normal limits.
No abnormalities are noted at the included osseous structures.
Conclusions: Normal thorax. No cause for the clinical signs is identified.

Findings:
3-View Thoracic/Abdomen Radiographic Study: The images are not labeled for laterality. 

Cardiovascular structures are normal. 
There are numerous small round, indistinctly defined to well-defined soft tissue to centrally gas cavitated and thin peripherally soft tissue nodules or dilated bronchi/bronchioles throughout the pulmonary parenchyma. There is mild ill-defined soft tissue thickening of the bronchial walls. 
There is mild gas within the pleural space caudoventrally and caudodorsally, causing mild retraction of the lung lobes from the thoracic wall. 
No abdominal organomegaly.
The stomach is mildly filled with gas. The pylorus fills normally with gas on the left lateral image. The small intestines are multifocally mildly filled with homogeneous soft tissue opacity and mild gas with no evidence of two populations of the bowel. The large intestine is multifocally filled with heterogeneous fecal material and gas.
The liver, splenic, renal, and serosal margins are normal.
Likely incidental spondylosis deformans. 

Bilateral Hindlimb and Pelvic Radiographic Study: The images are not labeled for laterality. 

There is marked osteophytosis of the stifles bilaterally. There is a large ovoid soft tissue mass caudal to and abutting the caudal margins of the suspected left stifle that extends caudally, effacing the crural muscles and then proximally and distally tapering to normal. There are regional indistinct wispy soft tissue striations. 
No other significant findings are identified.
Conclusions:
Numerous cavitated metastatic pulmonary nodules (e.g., carcinoma > sarcoma) or marked multifocal saccular bronchiectasis with mucus plugging, unlikely infectious etiology (e.g., lungworm such as Paragonimus, fungal).  Secondary/concurrent mild pneumothorax.
Chronic lower airway disease (e.g., asthma, chronic bronchitis).
Caudal crural (suspected left) soft tissue mass with regional steatitis is most likely neoplasia (e.g., carcinoma, sarcoma > soft tissue sarcoma), less likely abscess. 
Bilateral stifle degenerative joint disease.

Findings:
Tarsi 
Lateral and DP views dated 1/20/2025 are available (5 images). 

There is marked periarticular soft tissue swelling of the right tarsus, which appears to be predominantly (if not solely) intracapsular in nature. There is moderate periarticular new bone formation associated with all of the right tarsal bones and surrounding the tarsometatarsal joints. The new bone formation distally in the tarsus is smooth; however, there is some more spiculated new bone formation along the lateral aspect of the right tarsus. The right popliteal lymph node is moderately enlarged and rounded. The left tarsus is normal.
Conclusions:
Right tarsal changes and regional lymphadenopathy, in conjunction with provided cytology results and discussion with an orthopedic surgeon, are most consistent with septic arthritis. This cases was discussed with one of our orthopedic surgeons (Dr. Karl Maritato) and he said that it is fairly common to not get growth on culture in cats with septic arthritis so this does not exclude this disease process. The primary neoplastic process I would have considered is tarsal lymphoma, which should have exfoliated well and been apparent on the previously performed cytology making neoplasia unlikely at this time. Additionally, given that only one joint is affected, an autoimmune-mediated arthritis is considered unlikely. Dr. Maritato recommended treating with an antibiotic that has 4 quadrant coverage and if a clinical response is observed to treat for at least 8 weeks. 

Consider consultation with an orthopedic surgeon if additional discussion of treatment options is required. 
 
Thank you for your referral of this case for radiographic interpretation. Please contact me via email (chase.constant@medvet.com) if you have any questions or concerns related to this report. Be advised that I typically work Tuesday-Friday and emails received outside of these days may result in a delayed response.

Findings:
THORAX (opposite lateral, ventrodorsal views, 3 images total): The cardiac silhouette is borderline generally enlarged and there is an equivocal small bulge in the area of the left atrium on the lateral views that is  not conclusively corroborated on the ventrodorsal view.  The pulmonary vessels and pulmonary parenchyma are normal.  No conclusive intrathoracic lymphadenopathy or pleural lesions are identified.  No aggressive skeletal lesions are observed.  No tracheal lesions are identified within the field of view.

ABDOMEN (lateral view, 1 image total): The discernible aspects of the liver, spleen, kidneys, are normal.  No gastrointestinal abnormalities are identified.  The urinary bladder is not conclusively delineated, presumably due to minimal urinary bladder distention and superimposition of intestinal segments and pelvic limb musculature.
Conclusions:
*   Equivocal  left atrial enlargement and borderline generalized cardiomegaly. No evidence of congestive heart failure.  Given the murmur, cardiology consultation and echocardiogram is recommended to further evaluate.  
*   A conclusive cause of the patient's cough and lethargy is not identified on this exam, but both clinical signs could possibly be due to cardiac disease. 
*   Normal abdomen based on the single lateral view.  Three-view orthogonal radiographs are recommended if more conclusive evaluation is warranted.

Findings:
3-View Thoracic Radiographic Study: Compared to 2/17/2023.

Cardiovascular structures are normal.
The previous alveolar pattern within the left caudal lung lobe is resolved. 
There is similar mild ill-defined soft tissue thickening of the bronchial walls, mild dilation of the cranial lobar bronchi, and subtle lack of tapering toward the periphery. 
No metastatic disease or pneumonia. 
Pleural space and mediastinum are within normal limits.
No abnormalities are noted at the included osseous structures.
Likely incidental spondylosis deformans. 
Multiple variably sized lateral external thoracic subcutaneous fat opaque masses are present.
Conclusions:
No metastatic disease or pneumonia.
Persistent bronchial pattern (e.g., chronic bronchitis > age-related changes) with mild bronchiectasis or artifact. 
Likely multiple SQ lipomas. Cannot rule out soft tissue masses.

Findings: ABDOMEN (opposite lateral, ventrodorsal views, 3 images total): The stomach is mildly distended gas and fluid.  All small intestinal segments are normal in size, most being mildly to moderately distended with fluid and gas.  A few segments contain small volumes of granular soft tissue opaque material stippled with gas opacities.  On the ventrodorsal view in the right lateral mid abdomen, there is focal abrupt narrowing of the lumen of the small intestine as one views the intestine from cranial to caudal, and a thin curvilinear fluid line, potentially representing the wall of gas bubble within the smal intestinal lumen, is observed.  This focal narrowing is not conclusively identified on the lateral view.  The colon is moderately distended with fluid and granular soft tissue opaque material as well as gas proximally and granular soft tissue opaque material stippled with gas and granular and angular mineral opacities distally.  Some fluid opacity consistent with diarrhea is also observed.  The liver, spleen, kidneys, and urinary bladder are normal.  Abdominal serosal detail is normal.
Conclusions:
*   No evidence of gastrointestinal obstruction.  
*   Granular and angular mineral opaque content in the colon suggest recent dietary indiscretion that likely resulted in irritation of the gastrointestinal tract during passage and thus the patient's clinical signs. Therefore, gastroenteritis is considered the most likely differential for the patient's clinical signs at this time.
*   Fluid content in the colon is consistent diarrhea.
*   The abrupt narrowing of the small intesinal lumen on the ventrodorsal view in the right mid abdomen is believed to be a transient artifact of peristalsis rather than static lesion and this finding is believed to be insignificant. 

If clinical signs do not abate with symptomatic care, abdominal ultrasound is recommended for further work up.
